article.description: Tyra White scored 15 points, including 10 during the decisive first half of Texas A&M's (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today, No. 4 AP) 94-45  victory against Texas State on Saturday night.
article.headline: No. 3 Texas A&M cruises to keep record perfect
article.linkText: No. 3 Texas A&M off to school record 9-0 start
article.story:
COLLEGE STATION, Texas -- With final exams finally out of the way, Texas A&M (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today, No. 4 AP) taught Texas State a lesson in defense.

The Aggies whipped the Bobcats 94-45 Saturday night, limiting Texas State to a lone basket while building a 23-2 lead in the first 10 minutes.

"They're a great defensive team, and they showed that again tonight," Texas State coach Suzanne Fox said. "We struggled on the offensive end with their pressure. It was a great learning experience for us."

The Aggies, off to a school-record 9-0 start, had 10 steals in the first half, including two each by Takia Starks, Danielle Gant, Sydney Carter and Kelsey Assarian. They led 50-21 at halftime.

"The score got out of hand, but I'm not going to slow my kids down," Texas A&M coach Gary Blair said. "I just wanted them to work on their execution."

In the decisive first half, A&M freshman guard Tyra White scored 10 points on 4-of-6 shooting and ended up leading the Aggies with 15 points.

La Toya Micheaux, Adaora Elonu and White combined to snare 27 rebounds for A&M, and the Aggies' 59 total rebounds tied a Reed Arena record. Micheaux recorded her fourth career double-double with 11 rebounds and 10 points.

"We had six kids score in double figures," Blair said of A&M's season high in points. "If you've got a bench, you play your bench and you trust it. The kids are having fun."

Kim Cessna scored the first nine points for Texas State (4-5), and was just one of three Bobcats to score in the first half.

"It really doesn't matter to us how many points we're up by," said A&M point guard Sydney Colson, who recorded her first career double-double with 13 points and 11 assists. "We know our points are going to come on the offensive end. We want to hold teams under 50, to make it easier on ourselves."

The Aggies have won 35 consecutive nonconference home games dating to 2004. They're off until No. 19 TCU comes to College Station on Dec. 21.

"I'm pleased with this ball team," Blair said. "That team [Texas State] is a lot stronger than it looked. We played very well. The thing that I'm not going to like is that we've got seven days before we play again."
